<p style="margin-top: 1em"><b>--getvar|-v</b>
<i>&lt;variable&gt;</i> Get <i>&lt;variable&gt;</i> from
current theme.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em"><b>--new|-n</b>
<i>&lt;name&gt;</i> Create theme <i>&lt;name&gt;</i>.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em"><b>--list|-l
themes|vars|varmenu|default|current</b></p>


<p align="center" style="margin-top: 1em"><b><img src="grohtml-4115561.png" alt="Image grohtml-4115561.png"></b></p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em"><b>--updatelist|-u</b> Update
the rofi theme list</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em"><b>--clean|-C</b>
<i>&lt;directory&gt;</i> Remove all the generated theme
files in
<i>&lt;directory&gt;</i><b>/.themer/</b><i>&lt;name&gt;</i>.
If no <i>&lt;directory&gt;</i> is specified, then all
directories in <b>$THEMER_DIR/_dirs</b></p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em"><b>--help|-h</b> Display this
help.</p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em"><b>$ themer
--list default <br>
name default <br>
guifont $romanfont <br>
font CMUTypewriterText <br>
sansfont Lucida Sans <br>
monofont CMU Typewriter Text <br>
romanfont Luxi Mono <br>
ltimex 1 <br>
ltimey 90 <br>
size 11 <br>
rxvtsize 12 <br>
rofifsize 12 <br>
gtk Standard-light <br>
gtk-icon Tela-red-dark <br>
cursor Bibata_Dark_Red <br>
conky_loc1 top_left <br>
conky_loc2 bottom_right <br>
acc #285577 <br>
bg0 #CDCBCD <br>
fg0 #302f30 <br>
red #cc241d <br>
ylw #904800 <br>
blu #004890 <br>
grn #009048 <br>
cyn #009090 <br>
gnt #900048 <br>
rng #d65d0e</b></p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">Using themer -n will prompt to
create the required fg0 [foreground], bg0 [background] and
acc [accent] colour variables.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">The rest of the variables will
be taken from the <b>$THEMER_DIR/_default</b> theme, created
automatically, when the theme is generated. The
<b>_default</b> theme can be changed as you wish.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">You can also reference variables
using a <b>$</b> in front of the variable name in the theme
file and you can also mix colours.</p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em"><b>$ cat
~/.config/themer/dosnerd <br>
name dosnerd <br>
bg0 #DFBF9F <br>
acc #d5715e <br>
fg0 #1F1F1F <br>
blu $acc <br>
mix colmix 33:$bg0 66:$acc</b></p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em"><b>$ themer
--change dosnerd <br>
$ themer --list current <br>
%%name%% dosnerd <br>
%%bg0%% #DFBF9F <br>
%%acc%% #d5715e <br>
%%fg0%% #1F1F1F <br>
%%blu%% $acc <br>
%%mix%% colmix 33:$bg0 66:$acc</b></p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">to change the current theme and
generate all variables. If no theme is specified, you are
prompted with the below rofi menu:</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">[[/images/thememenu.png|themer
&ndash;change]]</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">including fg0, bg0, and acc
variations. These variations can be seen below.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">Use <b>themer --list vars</b> or
<b>themer --list varmenu</b> to see all the variables of the
current theme. <b>rofi</b> is invoked with
<b>-normal-window</b> flag with the latter option so you can
have this menu open and copy variables manually:</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">[[/images/varmenu.png|themer
&ndash;list varmenu]]</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">Add <b>--dark</b> or
<b>--auto-dark</b>
<i>&lt;am_time&gt;</i><b>:</b><i>&lt;pm_time&gt;</i> to
convert to a dark theme (just swaps <b>fg0</b> and
<b>bg0</b> and renames the theme to
<i>&lt;name&gt;</i><b>-dark</b>), or uses light/dark version
based on time of day, respectively.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">For example, an
<b>.Xresources</b> theme:</p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em"><b>$ cd $HOME
<br>
$ themer --init <br>
$ cp .Xresources .themer/template_.Xresources <br>
$ mv .Xresources .Xresources_old # backup! <br>
$ tree $HOME <br>
/home/user <br>
&#9500;&#9472;&#9472; .themer <br>
&#9474;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#9492;&#9472;&#9472;
template_.Xresources <br>
&#9500;&#9472;&#9472; .Xresources_old <br>
&#9500;&#9472;&#9472; .themer_pre <br>
&#9500;&#9472;&#9472; .themer_post <br>
&#9482;</b></p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">Here&rsquo;s my
template_.Xresources</p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em"><b>$ cat
~/.themer/template_.Xresources <br>
!! vim:ft=xdefaults <br>
#define cwhtl %%fg0%% <br>
#define cwhtd %%acb%% <br>
#define credd %%red%% <br>
#define credl %%red%% <br>
#define cgrnd %%grn%% <br>
#define cgrnl %%grn%% <br>
#define cylwd %%ylw%% <br>
#define cylwl %%ylw%% <br>
#define cblud %%blu%% <br>
#define cblul %%blu%% <br>
#define cgntd %%gnt%% <br>
#define cgntl %%gnt%% <br>
#define ccynd %%cyn%% <br>
#define ccynl %%cyn%% <br>
#define cblkd %%bg0%% <br>
#define cblkl %%bg1%% <br>
#define fontname %%font%% <br>
#define fontsize %%rxvtsize%% <br>
#define fontsize2 %%rxvtsize%% <br>
*background: cblkd <br>
*foreground: cwhtl <br>
*fading: 30 <br>
*fadeColor: black <br>
*cursorColor: credd <br>
*pointerColorBackground: cblkd <br>
*pointerColorForeground: ccynd <br>
*border: cblkd <br>
*color0: cblkd <br>
*color1: credd <br>
*color2: cgrnd <br>
*color3: cylwd <br>
*color4: cblud <br>
*color5: cgntd <br>
*color6: ccynd <br>
*color7: cwhtd <br>
*color8: cblkl <br>
*color9: credl <br>
*color10: cgrnl <br>
*color11: cylwl <br>
*color12: cblul <br>
*color13: cgntl <br>
*color14: ccynl <br>
*color15: cwhtl</b></p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">The variables from the current
theme can be listed using <b>themer --list vars</b>, and are
to be referenced with:
<b>%%</b><i>&lt;variable&gt;</i><b>%%</b>.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">Add RGB after a colour name to
get its RGB value in &ldquo;R, G, B&rdquo; form eg.
<b>%%bg0RGB%%</b>.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">Use <b>@@color@@</b> instead of
<b>%%color%%</b> to get hex color without &lsquo;#&rsquo;.
Useful for <b>#AARRGGBB</b> colours.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">The .themer_pre and .themer_post
bash scripts in the <i>&lt;directory&gt;</i> are used to do
things before/after applying the theme eg. reload the
.Xresources file (below) etc. These scripts have the current
theme name, eg. <b>dosnerd</b>, as their first argument.
Obviously, the shebang can be changed. My <b>.Xresources</b>
.themer_post is shown below.</p>


<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em"><b>#!/usr/bin/env
bash <br>
#requires you to use urxvtd &amp; urxvtc <br>
#see budlabs &quot;Let's Linux #021: urxvt
reload-config&quot; <br>
#https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=37jo_x6bXBk <br>
XRS=$HOME/.Xresources <br>
cat &quot;.themer/${1}/.Xresources&quot; | sed
&quot;s/\%\%.*\%\%//g&quot; &gt;</b> $XRS <br>
xrdb -load $XRS <br>
kill -1 $(pidof urxvtd)</p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em"><b>themer -a
$HOME</b></p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">to apply the theme to each
template in <b>$HOME/.themer</b>.</p>

<p style="margin-left:8%; margin-top: 1em"><b>themer
--apply-all</b></p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">to apply the current theme to
all directories in <b>$THEMER_DIR/_dirs</b>. Running
<b>themer --init</b> <i>&lt;directory&gt;</i> automatically
adds <i>&lt;directory&gt;</i> to this file, and if the
<b>--force</b> flag is added, &lsquo;FORCE
<i>&lt;directory&gt;</i>&rsquo; is added to
<b>$THEMER_DIR/_dirs</b>, to force-apply of the current
theme to a specific <i>&lt;directory&gt;</i>.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em">Both of the above options will
result in the following directory structure for our dosnerd
theme <b>.Xresources</b> example. Both options will also run
the <b>.themer_pre</b> &amp; <b>.themer_post</b> scripts
too.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 1em"><b>sh &#9474; $ cd $HOME &#9474;
$ tree $HOME &#9474; /home/user &#9474;
&#9500;&#9472;&#9472; .themer &#9474; &#9474;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&#9500;&#9472;&#9472; dosnerd &#9474; &#9474;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&#9474;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#9492;&#9472;&#9472; .Xresources
&#9474; &#9474;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#9500;&#9472;&#9472;
dosnerd-dark &#9474; &#9474;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#9474;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&#9492;&#9472;&#9472; .Xresources &#9474;
&#9474;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#9492;&#9472;&#9472;
template_.Xresources &#9474; &#9500;&#9472;&#9472;
.Xresources_old &#9474; &#9500;&#9472;&#9472; .Xresources
&#9474; # the new .Xresources! &#9500;&#9472;&#9472;
.themer_pre &#9474; &#9500;&#9472;&#9472; .themer_post
&#9474; &#9482; &#9474;</b></p>


